ty is her story--a tale told on many levels: personal, anthropological, legal, and, finally, political. The book's central chapters describe Hirsch's experience of the bombing trials in a Manhattan federal court in 2001, including a behind-the-scenes look at the investigation leading up to the trial, encounters with some of the FBI's leading terrorism investigators, and many moments of drama from the proceedings themselves. Hirsch reveals the inner conflict that results from her opposition to the death penalty and concludes that the trial was both flawed and indispensable. Hirsch's story of this tragedy and its legal aftermath comes to life through--and is enhanced by--her skills as a social scientist. Her unique viewpoint makes it unlike any other story about terrorism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAccountability Review Board.  aAlbright, Madeleine.  aBaugh, David.  aBergman, Jeanne.  aBorradori, Giovanna.  aClark, Ramsey.  aClassified Information Procedures Act.  aCornell, Christine.  aDerrida, Jacques.  aEast Africa.  aElshtain, Jean Bethke.  aFBI agents.  aFrancisco, Gerard.  aFreeh, Louis.  aGeneva Convention.  aGoldman, Laurence.  aHart-Rudman Commission.  aInternal Revenue Service.  aIslam.  aIslamic law.  aKenya.  aKiswahili.  aLayish, Aharon.  aMinow, Martha.  aMiranda rights.  aMombasa (Kenya).  aNational Public Radio.  aOklahoma City bombing.  aPemba.  aRahman, Omar Abdul.  aRwanda.  aSalameh, Mohammad.  aSufism.  aTuerkheimer, Frank.  aanthropology.  adeath penalty.  adefense attorneys.  aedda, waiting period.  aembassy bombings investigation.  afaith.  afuneral.  agrief.  ahuman rights.  ajustice.  alegal systems.  amatanga.  amourning.  amujaheddin